AUDIO: 'And we are also running bi-weekly HeyGen support office hours. So, keep an eye out for those. You can find those on our events page. Look out for emails. And we\'d have be happy to have you at'

[01:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'those as well. I I\'m so excited to have Julia with us. I\'m going to bring her on stage right now. &gt;&gt; Hello, hello Audrey.'

[01:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Thanks for joining us today. &gt;&gt; Yes, I\'m thrilled to be here. I never do anything live anymore cuz you know I don\'t have to with my clones. Wait, is this Julia? Is this a clone? How would we know?'

[01:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Yeah, is that real Julia? &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; I\'m just so excited to have you. If anyone is new here, I mean, I have to say I have heard from the community about you for I think over a year now of people saying that they found out about'

[02:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'HeyGen from your channel. But if anyone is not familiar, Julia is the founder and CEO of First Movers and she is an incredible AI video creator behind her channel, a community'

[02:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of nearly 300,000 YouTube subscribers. So, all powered by her digital twin. &gt;&gt; Yes, indeed. &gt;&gt; Absolutely amazing. Um'

[02:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Thank you. &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; And I would love to know, I mean, I I would love to just start with the conversation around like you obviously at 300,000 YouTube subscribers, you are one of the leading voices in AI-powered content today.'

[02:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But would love to take if you could take us back to what first convinced you to experiment with AI avatars with HeyGen, like what really started your journey on that journey? &gt;&gt; Yeah. Yeah, absolutely. Yeah, I got a chance to pick at the questions ahead of'

[03:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'time, so your team has been amazing for that. And I was thinking like, what\'s the best way to answer this because like there\'s so many different approaches to a digital twin and mine somehow worked out about 10 times better'

[03:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'than I could have expected. And when I think about the path there, like it started it didn\'t start with a digital twin, it started with what I knew about content and how I applied that to a clone. And so,'

[03:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'back in 2013, going way back here, &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; times have changed so much, wow. We built one of the first digital content writing agencies that had an e-commerce platform. So, we were one of'

[03:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the first to create this team of over 100 writers and sell writing as a service and built a self-service platform for our clients, had 5,000 clients, we did sometimes 200 projects a week. So, we got to see what actually'

[03:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'worked with content at a first-hand level. And along that journey, that was a 10-year journey, sold that agency in 2021 before ChatGPT came out and we kind of had this iPhone moment where we could'

[04:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'talk to artificial intelligence as if it was a human, which had never happened before. And to power that, we had the generative pre-trained transformer, which is the next level of how we use the machine. So, when all that happened'

[04:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '2 years prior, I was like, you know, I think the machines are probably going to take knowledge work. &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; And I bet on that even though article spinners were absolute garbage. Uh so, I made that bet, sold the agency,'

[04:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and it was the best thing I could have done. And what I decided to do was not just jump into AI and become an AI founder because I knew nothing about AI. I went from content writing and technology to something that'

[04:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'felt brand new. So, I started out by looking for the technology stack that would replace me. And I was known for this. It was hilarious. People would bring me on stage. I did over 27 talks'

[04:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'as the president of this company in 2024. And the talks often look like, "Well, um Julia used to hate on the machines and talk how about how bad AI is because that\'s how it started. It was'

[05:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'garbage. And now she\'s the president of the company that replaced her." &gt;&gt; [laughter and gasps] &gt;&gt; And it was the best conversation. It was a crazy year. So, did over 30 flights, and that fall, I saw something happen. I'

[05:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'saw the frontier models on their own capable of doing knowledge work. And so, I stepped completely out of software predicting another boom. I was right on the money.'

[05:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Company I worked for is no more, and the frontier models are literally as good as writers. And so, in that same month, um it was fall 2024, I saw digital avatars having a real potential use case. And it'

[05:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'was a tweet from HeyGen on X. I guess you can still say tweet and X. I never know anymore. But it was a tweet on X Xposed, I guess, and it was a real use case of somebody showing, the founder I'

[05:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'believe, showing how to completely clone yourself and it still looks and sounds just like you. And so I was like, this is actually the first usable case I\'ve seen where I think we can apply this to'

[06:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'work. And so I jumped in early. I\'m an early adopter, but it has to work. I come from this perspective of you know, if it\'s not robust, then I\'m not even going to talk about it. And we do this'

[06:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on my YouTube channel. I won\'t even talk about it. I won\'t put out any hype. I refuse to just create a headline for the sake of a headline. It has to work because for 13 years I\'ve built an audience of people that know Julianne'

[06:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'knows content and she knows organic marketing. And if she\'s going to recommend something, it\'s going to work and I\'m going to go all in. So I have this long-term trust. I wrote one of the first books on practical content strategy. So knowing I carry all this'

[06:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'trust, I\'m like, there\'s 50 million tools I will not recommend. I don\'t care if they pay me a $5,000 a video. Not going to do it. And so we test all the tools. And this one we set up I set up an avatar. I think it was December of'

[07:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '2024. We paired it with one of the best voice clone softwares, which was 11 Labs. Put that into HeyGen through API, connected those two things. I looked at it. I\'m like, wow. This actually looks'

[07:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and sounds just like me and it\'s a pretty good experience. And of course, the more minutes you get with the clone back then, the more glitchy it got. So we just covered that with really good B-roll. So we put out a video on my channel in the fall of 2024.'

[07:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I think it was December, the third week of December, right around Christmas. And that whole video was a clone. It was the first time I ever put a clone on my channel. And at the end of the video, the last 3 minutes, it was about some I'

[07:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'think it was the 01 model that came out from ChatGPT back then. It was breaking news and at the end of that video, I say, the real me comes on and I say, and I\'m wearing the same shirt, same outfit'

[07:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that the clone wore, I say, that 13-minute video you just watched wasn\'t me. It was a clone we built with HeyGen. And like, got to keep in mind, no one was doing this on YouTube. We were probably one of the first ones. So, we had this insane retention rate and that'

[08:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'month we had 30,000 subscribers. It was a massive growth month. And so, we had this retention rate where people would go back and watch the video three times. And that single video was like this massive accidental growth'

[08:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'machine cuz people had to rewatch it and go, what? Wait, this isn\'t you? &gt;&gt; Yeah. &gt;&gt; And that was that was the start of the journey. But, the main thing was like HeyGen actually worked. You know, we could feed it training data and actually'

[08:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'get a usable 10-minute video even though it\'s an avatar, a little bit glitchy, you can cover it with B-roll and make something beautiful. &gt;&gt; Yeah. And I mean, and you\'re you do use'

[08:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it in such a beautiful way. Like your videos, they are so natural. I sometimes watch them and I especially when you released your like updated clone, your digital twin, I I did have to I was like, wait, is she doing live videos'

[08:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'now? Like that\'s how good it was. &gt;&gt; Yes, and we still have people in the comments today that go, oh Julia, this is such a great prank. You\'re just telling us this is your AI clone. We know it\'s you.'

[09:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'m like, keep thinking that. &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; Yeah. So good. Um, I mean, I would love to know from your perspective, because you come from a content background and you\'re really thinking about the'

[09:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'positioning and how important that is, especially when it comes to AI content, introducing it. Um, I would love to know about how you chose to introduce your digital twin to your audience, how you continue to do that in a way that feels'

[09:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'authentic to you. &gt;&gt; Yes. So, this was an accidental mega success as well. &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; Um it was pretty unreal. So, everything I do, it\'s like comes from this'

[09:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'perspective of oh, it has to actually work. And if it doesn\'t work, I refuse to do it. And by work, I mean like it has to grow your business. It has to translate to something that doesn\'t break. Um it has to be simple. It can\'t add to your workload. And AI used by the'

[09:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'majority of people usually does all of those things. Instead of lightens your load, makes your load heavier, but it\'s all about the right tools and how to use them. And so, one of the first things I'

[10:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'did when I put out my digital twin on YouTube and we tested it with that video where we told people, hey, this whole thing was a clone. And they went back and watched it and they couldn\'t believe it. We blew their minds. It was so wild.'

[10:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Um so, what I decided to do was, you know, there\'s so much I I like to make predictions. Sometimes they come true. I\'m like, you know, I think there\'s going to be an ocean of'

[10:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'avatars. And we see this kind of in politics, right? Like, is that actually something they said? We also see it on Instagram. We see it in TikTok. We see it in the algorithm where it\'s like something is positioned as real and it\'s not. It\'s'

[10:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '100% AI. But the problem is no one is telling us that. So, what I decided to do, um because I am somebody that plants flags. I have a lot of beliefs. I\'m very outspoken about them.'

[10:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; Um is I decided that in every single video we would say in the first minute, hey, you\'re watching the digital avatar of the real Julia. And while she\'s out doing things that matter, like healing, talking to clients, building strategy,'

[11:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'behind the scenes, doing better work than she\'s ever done, which is true, the avatar is here to give you the best in cutting news. And Julia reads every script and reads every comment, which some as the comments are in the'

[11:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thousands now, &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; like we should change this, but I still read everything on a daily basis. Um so, we put that out there and we have put that in the first minute of over 400 videos. And what that\'s done is that\'s'

[11:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'created this, I think, precedence for those of us that are in marketing that are going to rely on the digital avatar the way I\'ve done to really replace yourself and think of it like a twin. I'

[11:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'love that term. Where, you know, it\'s not you showing up, you\'re liberated from the grind. And if you\'re a founder, if you have a message to say, that message can be so hard to get out in the world if you take all that work on'

[12:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'humanly, cuz that\'s how I started. I was the YouTuber. It was a 90-hour work week. Oof, I thank god I\'m out of that. My clone\'s doing it. So, if you know the load that this is to scale a message that reaches millions of'

[12:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'people per month without ads organically, which is what we\'re doing, and builds trust in that way, then you know, like this is insane value to be able to build a clone in this way. But'

[12:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'how do you get people to trust it, right? And so, we did this accidental thing that I did, which was just based on integrity. Like I kind of want the world to know, "Hey, you\'re going to be watching content and that\'s not a real'

[12:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'person. And if you\'re going to know it, you\'re going to know it from me. I\'m going to tell you. And then I\'m going to tell you why. So, I can do better work." And that has gone so well, that\'s really um built trust. You know, we host our'

[12:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'masterminds here in Phoenix once a month called Clone Camp. We hear from people, you know, I &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; it\'s like, "Well, you know, I started watching your channel. I wasn\'t sure about the Star Trek costume."'

[13:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; One person said that. &gt;&gt; [gasps] &gt;&gt; But, you know, um the way you position the avatar, like I was able to take it seriously. And then the value of the content is why I kept coming back. And so, that was like, "Oh, okay. I'

[13:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'think we\'ve done this right." You know, cuz everything was a guess. Is this actually going to go over well? But I think in the end, like you\'re never going to speak to a robot. You\'re never going to try to get humanoids to buy from you. You\'re getting humans to buy'

[13:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from you. How do you build trust with them? You be honest. You have integrity about what you\'re doing, and then you just do it really well. And that has gone really well, better than expected. Although we still have people that are'

[13:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like, this is not a this is not a clone. You\'re just pranking us. Yeah. &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; No, I mean, I I love that. I think it is such a genuine like answer that like you you made that decision cuz it was authentic to you and how you wanted'

[14:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to present your content and and it resonates with people, right? It is what works. Like we all appreciate that and I think that\'s actually such a theme that I\'ve seen of like when AI'

[14:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'disclosure conversation comes up and I think a lot of new people wonder about that of should I disclose or how to go about it and I think approaching it from what feels right to you and also to know that the'

[14:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'audience appreciates it. The audience doesn\'t want to be deceived, right? Like I think we all know that. We\'re all human and know that and we care about the message. We should care about the content. &gt;&gt; Yes, and we got a lot of this since'

[14:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'COVID. Like it\'s like, wait, who can I trust? What voice can I listen to? How much of this is real? And our trust kind of got shaken in the last 6 years a lot as a nation, as a world, I think. And so'

[14:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s it\'s kind of up to us, I believe, the entrepreneurs, the creators, to help rebuild that trust. How can we do that in a way that\'s authentic? We have a huge opportunity to do that. That\'s what\'s amazing. In a world where trust'

[15:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is crumbling, if we are the ones that build trust, mega return, which is what we\'re seeing. &gt;&gt; That\'s awesome. I love that. Well, you\'ve been Yeah, you\'ve been on this journey and you also you help so'

[15:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'many people with AI clones setting them up in your masterclass. Um I would love if you could share, you know, with with audience, a lot of people are new to HeyGen, any like lessons learned, any mistakes along the way you encountered,'

[15:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or things you learned specifically around like AI video strategy, um, as you kind of gone through that. &gt;&gt; Yes, yeah, another great question. I think that probably one of the approach main approaches we see, you know, we'

[15:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have about 500 students in our AI labs, we teach this, we have a signature course in there called clone to scale, we\'re launching one called clone to cash this week, all about how we built an $80,000 separate from the business'

[15:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'income stream through YouTube, 100% based on the clone. It\'s insane. Um, so, one of the main mistakes we see is that people come in and they see the clone as a shiny object and they just'

[16:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'get started creating it. They don\'t have a business, they don\'t have a clear offer, they don\'t have a strategy, and they don\'t have internal foundation set up to support what will'

[16:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'happen when and if they start to get that reach, which reach is easy. It\'s a matter of 2 + 2. If you are consistent at great content, reach is going to happen. And with the digital twin, like, I\'ve never been more excited to live in'

[16:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a world where marketing is possible with the reach we can have, that you know, everyone in the world is on the internet, so we can literally reach everyone, and it doesn\'t have to be us filming anymore. I mean, that is'

[16:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I wake up [snorts] every day going, do I get to live in this world? No joke. It\'s an incredible opportunity. Um, so, when people approach the clone though as a shiny object and just something new they want to try, it'

[16:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'usually falls flat. There\'s no consistency, there\'s no success, and they\'re stuck paying for HeyGen going, why is this not working out? When for me, HeyGen is one of my favorite subscriptions we pay per month. Let me'

[17:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tell you. &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; Cuz if you can\'t tell, it\'s just amazing not to film again. Um, so, when you approach it differently and you have this um, approach of the clone is going to be'

[17:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a robust key feature in my marketing that replaces me as the founder, that takes me out of all the busy work of content creation, so I get to do better'

[17:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'work, well then you approach it differently. Because for us, the strategy was never, you know, how do we just get a clone up and running? It\'s how do we do great YouTube content? See the difference? So if we\'re if our goal'

[17:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is how do we do great YouTube content? Well, the clone is easy. It\'s just one piece of filming and it takes me out, so it\'s amazing. Um, and so whenever we look at it that way, it\'s all about the strategy of the'

[17:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'channel. What are we going to talk about? And one thing that I teach and you get this with me if you come to clone camp, we don\'t start with AI. We actually start with what are your beliefs about your industry that would'

[18:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'get people really listening. And often times those beliefs are something very contrarian, something that hasn\'t been heard before, something that\'s true to you, something that you might be worried the world would hate if you put out'

[18:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there. Guess what? &gt;&gt; [gasps and laughter] &gt;&gt; I have proven that wrong time and time again. I\'ve thought that our best pieces would be a really high value piece on AI news. No, it was the strange offbeat quantum faith-based our brains are'

[18:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'antennas video. &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; What? But that just like and that\'s happened for 15 months. We\'ve really studied this. So the more you can embed of like who you are, that\'s like and if you\'re'

[18:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thinking of the word digital twin, it\'s perfect because clone and twin actually means like your DNA. It doesn\'t just mean your face and your likeness. So if you start by building your beliefs and what I would start with is the best AI'

[19:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'writer, which is the frontier model known as Claude. There\'s no better AI LLM that understands the human way of thinking than Claude. It was built for that purpose. With a constitutional AI'

[19:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'at its heart that Dario and Daniela Amodei focused on when they left Open AI. Um too bad we don\'t have Fable. I really hope it comes back. And a video is coming soon about that to my channel.'

[19:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; [laughter] [gasps] &gt;&gt; From my clone, not me. So, when you approach, okay, we\'re going to build a strategy, we\'re going to write and create content that is great. And we\'re going to use the best models'

[19:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to do this, which every single script on my channel we start with Claude, and we have a trained Claude project with over uh I think it\'s like maybe 50 pages between all the training data of viral'

[19:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hooks, headlines from my channel, from the top channels out there. We\'ve studied all that, broken it down, fed that to Claude, and now I go to Claude every day and I\'m like, what are we going to talk about on YouTube? And I\'ll'

[20:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'either feed it something that\'s important to me, or I\'m like, Claude, just go run, because it\'s built up with so much training data and so much beliefs that I\'ve had over time. Um been using Claude for almost 3 years.'

[20:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And so, when you have that approach, like, how do we create great content, the whole theory and the whole strategy changes. Instead of, let me just get my clone live in a weekend. And we will have people in the labs they\'re like, well,'

[20:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they\'re on the live calls every week. I\'m going to get my clone live this weekend. I\'m like, well, how\'s your business strategy? What\'s your marketing strategy? Um okay, you know what? Don\'t do that clone this weekend. Start with your strategy.'

[20:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Where are you going to post? How often are you going to post? How are you going to show up? What\'s your end goal? Do you have all that hooked up to a website that\'s beautiful, that builds trust, that people can actually click on and engage with?'

[20:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'All those things are really important. And it\'s like kind of like business 101, which is not exciting to hear. &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; But it\'s it\'s the truth. It\'s the practical work. that lays your foundation, right? Yeah.'

[21:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Yes, yes. And when those things come together, then it\'s magic because you don\'t have to film, you don\'t have to sit there and script. Like we really have an automated pipeline, autonomous pipeline, where I just jump in and do 5'

[21:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'minutes of work per video. It\'s insane. And it\'s art and it\'s beautiful. And we have a human in that loop, right? My I could not do this without my video editor team. I have to give them a major'

[21:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shout out. You know, my videos would not be anywhere near as amazing as they are without human editors in the loop. And we have some amazing editors that love what they do, love experimenting with the new features like Avatar B. So,'

